x4freetext: Short abstract.
-Absolute measurement of the Pu-240(N,F),
Pu-242(N,F) and Np-237(N,F) cross sections
at 2.5 MeV incoming neutron energy.- (In French) -
4 MV Van de Graaff machine
operated at 2.5 MHz, proton burst width 1 ns.
Tritiated titane deposit on a gold backing.
The neutron flux is measured by the
detection of the recoil protons from the monitor
reaction in a telescope detector.
These protons are identified by putting
the events into a biparametric E-DE array.
Time of flight is used to select only
fission events associated with the neutron burst.
2-PI ionisation chamber filled with 90
percent argon and 10 percent methane for the
detection of the fission fragments.
.Data taken from main reference, Table 4
Correction for fissions due to neutrons
scattered in fission chamber (calculated by a MONTE
CARLO simulation)               4.7 %
Correction for fissions obtained in fission
chamber without tritium in the target      0.1 %
Correction for fission events without tritium
in the target (detector telescope)          0.6 %
Correction for Neutron attenuation in the
Ta-backing of the sample (detector telescope) 1.5 %
Correction for background without tritium in
the target (BF3 long counter)    0.4 %
Correction for background with shadow bar in
front of the detector (BF3 long counter)     3.05%
Correction for neutron attenuation
in the air (BF3 long counter)               2.7 %
Correction for neutron attenuation in the
hybrid detector (BF3 long counter)          2.7 %
Total error. All errors were added
quadratically.
Error of extrapolation to zero pulse height of
the fission spectrum           0.1 %
Error due to loss of fissions  0.03-0.1 %
Error due to fissions of scattered neutrons.
Error due to number of atoms in sample.
Error due to geometric factors in the fission
chamber                        0.5 %
G.C.
Date is corrected
Last corrections have been done - SM.

x4freetext: .Pu-F(3) produced by CBNM-Geel by evaporation
under vacuum onto a tantalum backing of 0.3 mm
thickness. The isotopic composition is given
in table 1 of the main reference, 0.0109
98.478 atomic % Pu-240, 0.4701 atomic % Pu-241,
0.3677 atomic % Pu-242, 0.0006 atomic % Pu-244.
The thicness of the sample was 44.33 micro-grams
per cm**2. The number of atoms was determined
by alpha counting in a well known geometry.
Value not given.
Proton recoil telescope
detector consisting of an E- and a DE- solid
state detector. It has a 10 microns thick
polyethylene radiator. The solid state detectors
are completely depleted with thicknesses of
respectively 50 and 100 microns. The analysis of
the number of atoms in the radiator was done by
Huffman (Colorado).
It is used for absolute neutron flux deter-
mination.
.Corrections are given in table 2 of main
reference.
- In the fission chamber
- extrapolation to zero pulse height of
the fission spectrum         1.27%
- Loss of fissions             0.35%
Corrections for events without polyethylene
radiator (telescope detector)   8.2 %
Correction for fissions due to other isotopes
(telescope detector)    1.78%
Includes all systematic errors in
the telescope, i.e. those from ERR-7 to ERR-11
Fissions due to other isotopes.
Error due to events without radiator
Error due to events without tritium in target
Error due to neutron attenuation in the
Ta-backing
Error due to number of hydrogen atoms
Error due to detector efficiency
0.75 percent.
Counting statistics including fission
